WEBVTT

00:01.195 --> 00:28.654
date and place of birth wilfred bruce truax i was 
born october 15 1922 in donna texas i went through

00:01.195 --> 00:28.654
school except for the fifth grade all of it there in 
donna the fifth grade i spent one semester in

00:01.195 --> 00:28.654
wisconsin and one semester in Waco, Texas. This 
had come about primarily because our house had

00:34.233 --> 00:40.884
burned that summer before.

00:43.788 --> 00:47.734
Was this a fire of natural origin? No, it came 
about, my dad was always experimenting and trying

00:47.935 --> 00:56.869
to improve things around the house. He was trying 
to get a water heater working and there was an

00:58.486 --> 01:08.158
explosion. He was out in the yard at the time of the 
explosion, but it apparently scattered fuel

01:08.218 --> 01:21.455
pretty good because by the time he turned around, 
the whole house was on fire. This must have been a

01:22.516 --> 01:25.860
fairly unsettling experience for the family. Did 
y'all lose all your possessions? Almost

01:29.917 --> 01:33.562
entirely. My dad got back in as far as the kitchen 
and the only two things I can remember is he pulled

01:34.043 --> 01:48.924
the drawer of the ordinary silverware we used and 
also carried out the electric cooker that we had.

01:50.206 --> 01:54.953
Other than that, why, and then of course a little 
bit of salvage of few pictures and this where they

01:56.148 --> 02:23.758
were in a deep stack that it have burned edges but 
not completely burned up and but nearly

01:56.148 --> 02:23.758
everything else this was of course in the 
depression 33 and it was amazing how good people

01:56.148 --> 02:23.758
were to us we

02:25.072 --> 02:26.935
took us in at various places. We stayed and what 
have you. Well, I think each of the kids' classes, I

02:33.225 --> 02:47.107
know mine specifically did, they all brought 
various things from home or knew. You feel that

02:48.028 --> 02:51.754
people took care of each other more then than they 
do now?

02:54.620 --> 02:57.444
I tend to believe this in a sense. Of course you got 
to keep in mind too though that this is the

02:58.245 --> 03:11.785
difference of a town of 3,000 against

02:58.245 --> 03:11.785
living in 150, 200,000 city.

03:15.310 --> 03:21.319
Everybody tended to be a little closer probably 
and know each other's problems more and This

03:22.244 --> 03:28.391
probably couldn't have happened really at a worse 
time during the deep part of the Depression.

03:31.395 --> 03:37.302
What was your father's occupation?

03:38.523 --> 03:41.827
As far back as I could remember, he was in the 
electrical business. At this particular time, he

03:42.167 --> 03:51.458
was working for David Wilson, an electrical 
contractor there in town. After we came back from

03:52.079 --> 03:57.787
Wisconsin and Waco, he went into business for 
himself. I see. And could you give us your dad's

03:59.830 --> 04:01.973
name? My dad was Tuxton Burrell Truax. Remember 
where he grew up? He grew up primarily out at

04:06.779 --> 04:12.627
Novice, which is about 15, 18 miles west of 
Coleman. And your mother, can you remember her

04:13.709 --> 04:19.336
name and where she grew up? My mother was... Ada 
Buckmaster, she grew up primarily in Wisconsin.

04:30.383 --> 04:33.928
She and dad met in New Mexico, where she was 
teaching school. But her father was a doctor and

04:34.809 --> 04:47.585
one time was head of the state and St. Asylum 
institution there in Wisconsin. I take it then

04:49.187 --> 04:51.870
your mother was fairly uneducated when Yes, she 
was. It's a little interesting that their 50th

04:53.401 --> 05:10.847
wedding anniversary, I met a man who, in New 
Mexico, she had had as a pupil, that they had just by

04:53.401 --> 05:10.847
accident run in there. He heard the clerk mention 
the name Truax in the grocery store. And this was,

05:16.355 --> 05:21.182
he remembered. my mother and renewed an 
acquaintance.

05:28.485 --> 05:29.506
Did your mother go to college? She did? I'm sure she 
did, but I'm really not this sure where. At

05:35.472 --> 05:38.274
Janesville, I think, but I'm not this positive.

05:41.557 --> 05:44.580
Well, when did you graduate from high school? I 
graduated from Donna High School in 1940.

05:49.613 --> 05:51.995
Do you remember anything about the high school 
there? The size? I believe, if I remember right,

05:53.937 --> 06:05.428
there were 320 in high school, and I believe there 
were 39 or 40 in our graduating class. Do you

06:07.530 --> 06:14.697
remember anything about your high school 
experiences, anything that comes to mind at that

06:07.530 --> 06:14.697
time? It might give some bearing on the education 
at that time. No, not really. We had

06:21.664 --> 06:36.162
just primarily one teacher to a subject type 
thing, and there was one or two of them.

06:39.246 --> 06:49.658
They'd always done real well in math in high 
school, and when I got to A&M, why, I decided that it

06:39.246 --> 06:49.658
was only because it had been so easy. And where 
chemistry, at that time at least, was considered

06:50.212 --> 07:03.624
kind of a bust-out course, I made B's in it because 
of a good foundation from a good instructor. You

07:03.704 --> 07:09.168
felt you were fairly well prepared then to enter 
college, then, from your grades? Yes, I was

07:09.449 --> 07:15.834
probably third or fourth in our high school class. 
As a freshman, I had the highest grades in the

07:21.346 --> 07:23.028
class. How did you wind up going to A&M? What 
motivated you to go there? I think primarily my

07:30.515 --> 07:34.920
father. I can't ever really recall him ever 
talking specifically about it, except that

07:35.460 --> 07:48.754
somewhere or another he had me convinced I wanted 
to go to college. I grew up working with him even

07:49.477 --> 07:59.227
before he went into business for himself, 
weekends and such as this. He was always one of

07:59.708 --> 08:09.578
great patience and would answer any kind of 
questions or what have you. And

08:11.119 --> 08:19.348
like I say, he had not even finished Well, I'm not 
sure how far he got, but I know he didn't finish high

08:20.358 --> 08:28.130
school, and I'm not sure he ever got to high school. 
And this was one of the things that he made

08:29.592 --> 08:47.800
every effort to convince me that I wanted to

08:29.592 --> 08:47.800
in a roundabout way, not pressuring you or the way 
that you would rebel and not want to go. I can

08:50.928 --> 09:01.458
remember writing themes in Spanish about wanting 
to go to A&M, major in engineering, and go to South

08:50.928 --> 09:01.458
America. Traveling

09:01.498 --> 09:09.666
in the service took the South America desire out 
some. However, I always liked traveling.

09:18.931 --> 09:21.034
What were your first impressions? First of all, 
when did you arrive at A&M, and what were your first

09:21.494 --> 09:27.342
impressions? Well, this is, I'm sure, in one 
sense, some different.

09:34.351 --> 09:47.908
Boy, at one time, my dad went to a short course with 
an Alton Bird, who lived there in Donner still, but

09:34.351 --> 09:47.908
long years ago, before I can remember, they were in 
an auto shop business together. And we went to,

09:52.735 --> 09:56.539
they went to a short course, and I went up there with 
them. And their son was, Mr. Bird's son was in

09:56.559 --> 10:02.745
college at that time. And immediately after I 
graduated from high school, that week following,

10:04.147 --> 10:18.402
I hitchhiked up there and spent a week with George 
Bird just before his graduation. In a sense, this

10:18.736 --> 10:48.152
was,

10:18.736 --> 10:48.152
well, it didn't have any real repercussions in 
that Burt Campbell, who was orderly for George as a

10:18.736 --> 10:48.152
freshman and George a senior,

10:18.736 --> 10:48.152
made up my bed, took me to breakfast meals and this 
sort of thing, When then in the following year I'm

10:49.145 --> 10:57.195
in the same company with Burt Campbell as a 
sophomore and me as an incoming freshman. I see.

10:59.358 --> 11:02.342
And when did, what did you start in the fall of 1940? 
In the fall of 1940. I see. I entered. What company?

11:08.110 --> 11:09.591
In headquarters signal company. And what was your 
major at this point? Electrical engineering.

11:14.558 --> 11:15.359
Electrical engineering. What do you remember 
from your freshman year? Was it particularly hard

11:18.271 --> 11:20.234
on you? Was the hazing severe?

11:26.362 --> 11:46.050
I'd always looked at the hazing a little different 
I guess than than lots in the they

11:26.362 --> 11:46.050
it appeared a good deal to me as far as you taking 
care of an upperclassman's room for a year and you

11:26.362 --> 11:46.050
get your room taken care of for three years and It 
seems like a good trade. Yeah, this is...

11:54.059 --> 12:05.232
I got caught eating cake when you shouldn't have 
and drank the castor oil and ate spinach. And, of

12:05.312 --> 12:16.324
course, I can remember trying to haze me drinking 
buttermilk, but I like buttermilk and I like

12:05.312 --> 12:16.324
spinach, so lots of these things didn't bother me 
like some of them. The chew in the back, I got sick.

12:25.732 --> 12:28.536
The hazing though was not particularly physical 
at this time. No, it was very physical much of the

12:28.876 --> 12:32.302
time. Of

12:32.322 --> 12:42.497
course the sophomores, were running it. The one 
thing that to me broke down later, and I often

12:46.089 --> 13:07.334
wondered if this is when they started going 
straight through and it wasn't that period

12:46.089 --> 13:07.334
between the end of your sophomore year and the 
beginning of the junior year and this, that they

12:46.089 --> 13:07.334
didn't want to quit. But as a freshman,

13:12.937 --> 13:18.545
In our company, at least, it was very resonant.

13:21.049 --> 13:25.636
Specifically, a senior could call for a freshman, 
and all freshmen could come running. A junior

13:26.878 --> 13:33.167
could call fish so-and-so, and that freshman 
would come running. A sophomore had to go get him a

13:33.187 --> 13:39.737
freshman if he wanted a detailed run.

13:42.164 --> 13:52.159
One of the worst things you could do would be not to 
speak to and or go meet friends of a senior. He

13:53.681 --> 14:01.573
didn't ever say anything to you, but he got him a 
junior and that junior got in several sophomores

13:53.681 --> 14:01.573
and the sophomores got all were freshmen. So that 
it was a strict type of chain of command, so to

14:02.835 --> 14:11.428
speak. Do you feel later why this seemed to break 
down and the juniors and seniors were hazing just

14:13.720 --> 14:24.814
as much as the sophomores were? Do you feel that the 
seniors or juniors kept the hazing in line? Did the

14:32.183 --> 14:34.385
sophomores do most of the physical hazing? Yes, 
the sophomores primarily did. Well, before the

14:39.674 --> 14:47.304
first football game, the company commander 
announced there would be a company meeting at the

14:39.674 --> 14:47.304
second floor in the hall there. With it, they lined 
up with boards, and the juniors went through, and

14:49.467 --> 14:57.437
the sophomores went through, and the freshmen 
went through, and they went on to football games.

14:58.339 --> 15:06.289
And then juniors lined up, and sophomores went 
through, and the freshmen went through, and they

14:58.339 --> 15:06.289
went on, and then the sophomores lined up. But 
primarily, the

15:08.986 --> 15:20.746
seniors and the juniors were the ones who 
controlled it, but they didn't do the hazing. And I

15:21.727 --> 15:24.111
say they didn't do the hazing. Some freshmen got 
real out of line. A senior would collar in a couple

15:27.497 --> 15:34.909
of juniors, and those juniors in turn that same 
chain of command to the sophomores. And the

15:38.317 --> 15:42.741
sophomores would have the whole freshman class in 
our company there. Keep in mind, though, that they

15:45.304 --> 15:50.348
did have some, in a sense, reverse outlets. 
Halloween night, the juniors came around and got

15:51.089 --> 15:54.592
the freshmen. And we out and dug a mud hole. And 
sophomores were free game then in our class. And

16:01.499 --> 16:04.862
they were hauled out and dumped the mud hole and it 
was it was not gentle to say the least they could

16:05.804 --> 16:35.676
fight and look there were always more freshmen 
than there were same way we'd have

16:05.804 --> 16:35.676
semi-controlled i guess you would say tackle 
football games with just towels for padding and

16:05.804 --> 16:35.676
that's all so that you did have some in a sense uh 
semi-legal opportunities to vent your anger at

16:36.432 --> 16:46.706
the sophomores, and yet the system still worked. 
Do you feel like you learned anything from this

16:47.907 --> 16:54.997
particular

16:47.907 --> 16:54.997
discipline, shall we call it? Do you feel like 
there was anything to be learned from this, that

16:55.017 --> 16:58.281
there was a point to it?

17:02.247 --> 17:04.009
I always felt that this was was one part of that that

17:05.474 --> 17:17.754
made you closer as a unit through your years there. 
Because almost, except

17:19.276 --> 17:32.578
for rare exceptions, and we had a couple who

17:19.276 --> 17:32.578
just delighted in hazing, I guess you'd say. But 
primarily, it was the chain of command type thing

17:33.605 --> 17:39.450
and not just indiscriminately. Hazing for 
hazing. Right. Now, I'm not sure that this is true

17:42.753 --> 17:46.036
on the whole campus by any means. I think that there 
are some of the other places where

17:46.516 --> 17:57.406
maybe it was a difference in the group. All of them, 
of course, in the Signal Corps at least started

17:57.546 --> 18:02.110
out. signed up for EE. They didn't all necessarily 
stay there all the way through, but this was the way

18:03.926 --> 18:11.015
you ended up in the Signal Corps to begin with. I 
see. Do you feel that maybe this taught you

18:12.877 --> 18:15.921
self-discipline in a way? Could it teach you to 
discipline yourself as far as having to follow

18:15.961 --> 18:20.006
certain rules and regulations? There were places 
you were supposed to be at certain times and things

18:20.046 --> 18:25.432
you did at certain times and things you did not do. 
Do you feel this way? I felt very definitely that it

18:26.474 --> 18:28.676
did. And it also The hazing bit

18:32.161 --> 18:55.202
was controlled, the study, and this is one of the 
places some of the stories you heard make you think

18:32.161 --> 18:55.202
then that it wasn't as controlled as some of the 
other units. Seven o'clock, call the quarters,

18:55.622 --> 19:02.168
you got at your desk and you stayed at your desk even 
if you had to prop your head up until 11 o'clock. The

19:06.028 --> 19:12.875
only place you could go would be to the restroom and 
back to your room, and that was it. You didn't go

19:13.415 --> 19:16.799
visit any other freshmen anywhere. You stayed in 
your room and were supposed to study. There was no

19:20.882 --> 19:30.872
time that any of the upperclassmen interfered 
with this study time, sending you on details or

19:20.882 --> 19:30.872
anything else. I gathered that this, as I said, 
didn't necessarily hold true to all the other

19:32.033 --> 19:38.903
units. Do you think this taught you how to study? 
How to discipline your time? Not really, but it was

19:43.990 --> 19:50.939
if you went ahead and used it, why it helped. And 
there was at 11 o'clock you went to bed, however

20:01.396 --> 20:09.224
I don't know if there was a specific time, but I've 
been up as early as 3 o'clock working on a drawing or

20:01.396 --> 20:09.224
something like this. And there never seemed to be a 
limit at what time you could get back up again. But

20:14.309 --> 20:16.631
you did go to bed at 11 o'clock and lights out. I see. 
Do you remember anything else about your freshman

20:19.033 --> 20:20.775
year? Any of the courses that were particularly 
hard? Well, primarily, of course, I did standard

20:25.740 --> 20:31.065
engineering, freshman engineering. 
curriculum.

20:36.051 --> 20:49.122
Trig, as I mentioned before, after I got up there, 
I'm not that sure of my math background since I

20:36.051 --> 20:49.122
don't remember ever having heard of Trig before I 
went to college.

20:55.187 --> 21:01.272
And the math, I guess, primarily was where I had my 
hardest time as a sophomore year busting

21:01.657 --> 21:30.550
the first semester I guess the second semester 
first semester of calculus is the only course I

21:01.657 --> 21:30.550
ever busted but did you lose a lot of people that 
first year out of your freshman class a lot as I

