30:57.678 --> 31:08.674
Corpus Christi and went back in the fall. And on 
this basis then, you didn't start. advanced ROTC

31:13.595 --> 31:26.606
at mid-turn, so I was actually then in December or 
approximately before I rejoined an ROTC unit. I

31:27.787 --> 31:33.131
lived in

31:27.787 --> 31:33.131
Goodwin Hall, I guess it was. As a civilian 
student? Yes. Did you have to wear a uniform? We

31:37.935 --> 31:43.500
still wore a uniform, but we were not in the Corps as 
such. So you were getting ahead academically

31:44.885 --> 31:48.150
ahead of your military then? Right. So then in the 
mid- then what was not mid-semester, when did you

31:49.572 --> 31:54.939
rejoin a unit now? Well actually it would be the 
beginning of my academic senior year, but it

31:56.361 --> 32:04.953
turned out it was my junior year. And then it was in 
this semester when we all went on active duty,

32:12.826 --> 32:20.135
all those who were in advanced ROTC. The units all 
left the campus for approximately a week, as I

32:21.157 --> 32:27.485
recall. Do you remember when this was? 
Approximately what day was it? March. March of 43.

32:37.718 --> 32:39.660
As mentioned before, you To be an advanced ROTC, 
you had to be an enlisted reserve, and this was a

32:41.058 --> 32:47.526
matter of calling up the enlisted reserve. I see. 
From A&M,

32:49.910 --> 32:57.800
units went various places.

33:00.564 --> 33:04.449
In the Signal Corps, we went to Camp Beauregard, 
Louisiana. There were those who went to Camp

33:04.549 --> 33:07.032
Walters. those went to Fort Sam Houston. These 
were all induction centers.

33:15.855 --> 33:17.276
Where did you go? I went to Beauregard, Louisiana. 
For how long? It took about a week. We went through

33:22.643 --> 33:34.977
the standard battery of tests and were issued in 
uniforms and taken down to Camp Livingston for

33:22.643 --> 33:34.977
inoculations, and then put on a train back to the 
campus and we finished our regular semester. Were

33:40.285 --> 33:42.068
you on active duty and being paid? Yes. The whole 
time? Just after we were called active duty. And

33:46.494 --> 33:49.938
what rank did they consider you all as? As a 
private. As a private, and they were paying you all

33:50.619 --> 33:52.642
as private? Right. I see. Okay, after you came back 
to the campus, you went ahead and finished that

33:54.825 --> 33:57.989
semester? We finished our regular classes that 
semester and immediately after at the end of the

34:04.572 --> 34:09.219
term scattered to the winds again. Those, and here 
again I'm talking now not class of 44, because I, in

34:09.280 --> 34:27.208
this ROTC business, I was really with the class of 
45, having missed a year of ROTC. But all of these in

34:28.531 --> 34:32.537
this class went to various training camps for 
basic training before going to OCS. Those who were

34:41.301 --> 34:51.297
actually in the class of 44 went directly, and I say 
directly, almost directly to OCS, I believe.

34:53.921 --> 34:55.403
What camp did you go to? There was a train load of us. 
We first went to Fort Sam, and then from there on a

34:58.791 --> 35:04.379
train to Camp Roberts, California. As the story 
goes, I wasn't there, but supposedly some of them

35:05.501 --> 35:16.898
working in the supply room, the colonel came in and 
said, boy, there's been a mistake made. All of

35:16.918 --> 35:19.101
y'all are not supposed to have been here. Those of 
us there at the time were cavalry, Coast Guard

35:20.042 --> 35:25.390
cavalry, no, no field artillery. Calvary, Coast 
Artillery, Engineers, Signal Corps, and

35:25.640 --> 35:29.844
Infantry. And almost immediately, those of us 
that had been in Signal Corps over D.C. went to Camp

35:31.526 --> 35:39.873
Kohler close to Sacramento. The Coast Artillery 
went to Camp McQuaid, and the Engineers went on up

35:41.495 --> 35:49.382
to Camp Abbott in Oregon. And this was basic 
training? This was basic training. and was

35:54.226 --> 36:10.667
probably some of the best military

35:54.226 --> 36:10.667
training I ever had, and the company commander got 
out, y'all are ROTC, you're supposed to be able to

35:54.226 --> 36:10.667
know how to march, let's see. We marched, and he 
said, there's no sense in spending time on that,

36:11.669 --> 36:16.134
we'll go to something else. Fortunately, we went 
to Camp Kohler, they had a, training program set

36:22.643 --> 36:28.250
up, and we were doing things that we had done the 
first six weeks. We were in freshman ROTC. Did they

36:31.934 --> 36:33.376
keep the A&M people together? We stayed together, 
yes. You didn't have any people coming in from the

36:36.519 --> 36:38.522
outside? We had a few, and really you feel sorry for 
them because they were behind. Some of them,

36:45.870 --> 36:47.252
right. We had one or two draftees there at at Camp 
Roberts that were in a unit with, well, it was a

36:50.707 --> 36:59.560
whole battalion, training battalion, full of 
nothing but Aggies.

37:01.964 --> 37:06.050
So there was no way that they could do it. And 
eventually, as I recall, they got them

37:06.110 --> 37:09.475
transferred out.

37:13.461 --> 37:14.723
How long were you in basic training?

37:19.748 --> 37:22.852
Until September, I believe it was, October.

37:25.295 --> 37:30.301
It was supposedly the pretty much standard basic 
training. Do you remember how many weeks?

37:36.229 --> 37:37.250
Not for positive. It was about the middle of July 
when we went to Camp Kohler after having been there

37:37.370 --> 37:48.945
at Camp Roberts for about six weeks. I see.

37:55.021 --> 38:01.109
Somewhere about the first of October, we were 
assigned to an ASTP unit. We were sent back to A&M to

38:01.129 --> 38:06.397
be in the ASTP. What's an ASTP unit? Army Student 
Training Unit Program. Okay. You were sent back to

38:12.846 --> 38:14.528
the State College? Still as a group.

38:18.507 --> 38:26.596
I was presumed primarily because there wasn't an 
opening in OCS because after one semester of this

38:18.507 --> 38:26.596
we did go on to OCS. Now wait a minute, so you were 
back at A&M for another full semester then? For,

38:33.784 --> 38:46.658
right, it was a speeded up and these were, we ended 
up getting some hours credit just as a

38:48.899 --> 38:57.788
transcript shows full military referral ROTC 
credit by having gotten a commission. These hours

38:57.808 --> 39:02.473
were added to just as if you'd taken them there at 
A&M. Now, wait a minute. You're talking about

39:04.636 --> 39:06.177
getting a commission. After basic training, you 
still were not commissioned, were you? No. No. We

39:10.122 --> 39:11.903
went to the STP unit. Then from there, we went to 
Fort Monmouth, New Jersey to Signal Corps. Do you

39:18.447 --> 39:20.229
remember when this was? We went in February, right 
towards the end of February, and this was quite a

39:20.249 --> 39:27.496
change weather-wise. And it still has a unit to 
OCS? All of us in the Signal Corps, yes. The other

39:36.166 --> 39:41.271
units were going various directions, and I'm not 
positive that all of them came back. A number of the

39:42.092 --> 39:46.176
various different ones did come back.

39:49.345 --> 39:56.672
But I can't be positive about all of them coming to 
ASTP before they went to OCS. I know the group that I

39:57.733 --> 40:00.776
was with in the Signal Corps did. So you were at OCS 
for how long? I got out of OCS in June. Now your A&M

40:13.248 --> 40:17.412
training and all the other military training, did 
you have any trouble with OCS? No, not

40:19.096 --> 40:20.417
particularly. Were all the people here, your OCS 
training unit, were they A&M people? No, all of

40:28.567 --> 40:37.176
those of us in the ROTC were in this class, but there 
were some other classes.

40:40.800 --> 40:45.205
I don't remember ever seeing Mr. Foraker 
afterwards this. but one experience that I recall

40:45.556 --> 40:58.730
well was there was a group from Clemson, and they 
were talking about one of their prof and imitating

40:45.556 --> 40:58.730
him, and they said, well, that sounds like Four 
Acre. Well, it is Four Acre. It was my

41:01.853 --> 41:13.446
understanding that it was Four Acre's either twin 
brother or brother, but there were these from

41:01.853 --> 41:13.446
Clemson. There were a few from

41:15.492 --> 41:32.551
regular Army enlisted personnel that were there 
at OCS class, but primarily it was the two largest

41:15.492 --> 41:32.551
groups in our class, I think, were Clemson ROTC and 
A&M ROTC units. How did A&M ROTC units at this time

41:32.571 --> 41:36.715
stack up against the other schools? I think we did 
probably pretty close to equally well. We had I had

41:45.327 --> 41:48.192
two pretty close friends that busted out. The big 
problem primarily was barracks inspection while

41:48.232 --> 42:08.348
you were at class and having the closing button or 
some such thing as this and even work

41:48.232 --> 42:08.348
out trying to help and check them and that kind of 
thing and you'd get down for formation to go to

42:09.307 --> 42:23.382
class and they'd forgotten something and run back 
up and mess up something in their hurry and this

42:09.307 --> 42:23.382
sort of thing. The A&M people pretty much stick 
together over this then? Yes. Try to help one

42:26.966 --> 42:28.889
another through. Yes. So you got out of OCS in June? 
I believe this is right in June. Then you were

42:36.003 --> 42:38.827
commissioned at that point? At that point, 
commissioned, yes. Then what? I went to officer

42:43.232 --> 42:47.698
school for about six weeks. It was called Long 
Lines Inside, which is telephone equipment,

42:48.820 --> 43:03.499
switchboards, teletype, repeaters, this sort of 
equipment, and then was assigned to a unit. This

43:03.519 --> 43:05.301
was also at Fort Monmouth. and then was assigned to 
a casual detachment group that

